WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.000
You ready sir?

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Sure. Great question I can be.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:22.000
All right. Well good morning today is December 15th, 2015. This is David Cline from the History Department at Virginia Tech.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Also working with the Southern oral history program at UNC Chapel here. Hill.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And we are here this morning as part of the Civil Rights History Project of the Library of Congress.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
This Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Southern oral history program.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.000
And I have the great honor of being with Lt. Gen. Julius W. Becton Jr this morning.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And if you could just introduce yourself and this is the only time I'll script you at all.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
A full sentence to start with I am or that my name is.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
I'm Julius Wesley Becton Jr. Lieutenant General United States Army Richard.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Thank you. Happy.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:00.000
Thank you sir.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
So let's just if we start with the where you are born and raised in a little bit about your family.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And then we'll have a conversation and take it from that.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Okay. I was born in Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:21.000
I went to high school in Lower Merion in high school. I just point that out because there are a few rather prominent graduates of Lower Merion.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:34.000
The Librarian of Congress has an example of James H. Billington, Alexander Haig of some notoriety, Henry "Hap" Arnold, the former Commander of the Air Force, the former Air Corps.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:45.000
If you live here in Washington, the anchor on Channel 4 is a graduate of Lower Merion.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And we have other some prominent citizens.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Kobe Bryant, some people have never heard of him.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
I understand he's retiring this year.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
So we have that kind of program.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
We have some outstanding academics at one time.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Lower Merion was in the top 10 of the high schools in the country and they're still very hard now.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
And they have a great reputation.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
I'm happy to say that I get out of that place.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
It will.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And this is what they call the main line.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
The main line to fill it off you.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.000
It's supposed to be, not supposed to be, is it very gritty and well to do.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
I was born there because my father was a janitor in the department.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And we lived in the basement of the department.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And it's a block and a half from Bryn Mawr College.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And two blocks from Bryn Mawr train station that goes out from Philadelphia.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
It's a very other schools, Rosemont, Villanova, Kavrford, Swapwood,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
just some of the schools that are in that area.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
So they grew up in an academic field.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Right.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And what were the sort of restraints or boundaries of race and class in that area as you were growing up?

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:10.000
It was part of the segregation areas.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
However, the schools were not segregated.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
We could not go into certain restaurants or could not.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
We go to the theater.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
We were required to sit down in front rows.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And if there were fill, we just, depending on how much the field would feel,

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
the film would be going.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
We could remember, Mangle with Red the Folk, they wouldn't complain about it.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
But it was segregated.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
We're talking now back in the 20s and 30s.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
It took some time to get through all of those things.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.000
And so you had your high school years there.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And high school years, the Lower Merion located in Ardmore, Pennsylvania.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
It's a township.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
There were very few things we could not do.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
We could not participate in the swimming program.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.000
I do not remember in the four years I was in high school, county, ninth grade,

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
having gone to a prom.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.000
It wasn't encouraged.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So we did not bother doing it.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
We did not have to work in the four schools.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
We were concerned academically.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
We were encouraged to do the best we could.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
I happen to have been a member of the student council.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
The president of my class.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.000
We started kindergarten together and he'll be invited to my birthday party.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.000
We go back that four.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Wonderful.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:45.000
So after high school, after high school, I joined the Army Air Corps listed reserves

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
and I was a senior at Lord of Married.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:55.000
And when I graduated, I came on to do the, what year was this?

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:03.000
1944 when I came on to do the, my first duty station was the Luxe Mississippi,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Keesler Air Force Base.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:13.000
As I sometimes say with tongue and cheek, I greet a place for young black 18 years old to go to in those times.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And taking the physical examination for flight school, I flunked the ice test.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
I had stigmatism.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:25.000
I knew I had that problem.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:34.000
But when I walked into my testing in every other place, they had a big chart in a wall, big E, and then scale down.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And those days I could take one look at that chart and I had it memorized.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Front back either way.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
They said, okay, cover your right eye, cover your right eye.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Cover the left eye, fine.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.000
I got down a Keesler field, new machine, technology.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:58.000
In a darkened room with a machine right back here, and you walk in, I don't see any chart.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Room's dark.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
They pushed a button.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
The chart comes up.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
I had no chance.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
I flunked the test.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:18.000
And that sent me off to McDillfield, which was an Army Aviation Facility Engineer.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
What had you been hoping you might be able to do?

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.000
I wanted to become a pilot in what turned out to be a Tuskegee Airmen.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
Didn't have that name when I was there.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:36.000
I wanted to become a pilot because half-barnal had come out to our high school and convinced us

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
to join the Army Air Corps when you're silver wings and gold bars.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And I got out, I went down, and after he finished his spiel, about half the football team went down to take the battery of tests.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
Six of us passed.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And on the 28th of December, 1943, we were all inducted into the Army Air Corps and let's the reserves.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And that's how I got into the flight program in the first place.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:16.000
After going through New Cumberland, New Cumberland-Landwood with the reception station, I went to a Keesler Field.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
My five other buddies went to Florida.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Kiesler went ahead, black Americans, to Florida, they did not have.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:31.000
And so I might add that none of us became pilots for various reasons.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:40.000
After that, off the MacDill Field, Army Engineering.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:46.000
Well, let me ask first, you said it tongue in cheek, blocks you not the best place perhaps to be.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
Could you tell us a little bit about what conditions were there?

00:07:50.000 --> 00:08:02.000
For example, the one weekend I took off, we leave from Keesler Field, the buddy of mine, and I went down to Kiesler,

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:06.000
to Biluxy, rather, from the base.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.000
And while walking down the street, we heard some noise coming from the rear.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
There are two of them.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
And we turned around here, and the pickup truck coming down to payment, driving at us.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
We flat the guest walls, and they went by.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And we thought it may be a good idea to get back on post.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And so we did.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And that was typical treatment, treatment.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And I pointed out because many years later, I went back to Biloxi,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
I am now a Lieutenant General United States Army.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:46.000
I was invited back by the National Guard of Mississippi.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.000
I was greeted by the Agent General.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:56.000
I flew in in my own aircraft, the Army's aircraft, rather, which I control.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
I was greeted by this AG.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:10.000
We went from the airfield to a small camp that they had, and I forget to name it, a base, the Army of the Camp, rather.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:20.000
I spent the night there, and then we drove to the hotel where they had a meeting of National Guard,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
and reservists, for which I was to speak to.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And my first comment, my health, things have changed.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
And I explained what I was talking about.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
The last time I was down here, let me tell you what happened to me.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
And of course, all of them knew and understood what I was exactly talking about.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:48.000
I had a State Trooper escort from the airport to this camp, to the hotel, left in great fashion.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
But that wasn't a significant change.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:57.000
Still is not the best at a time, but it would help a lot better than when I was first there.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
What were the barracks like in 1944?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
It wouldn't build, wouldn't buildings, two story.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
Just like everyone else, but we were separated from the rest of the post.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:15.000
Control by the camp.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:21.000
My company commander was a white, first lieutenant.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:27.000
He had a white, exec, and the rest were black.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
First Sergeant, the rest of the cadres.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:38.000
As a matter of fact, it was there after I got down to McDill,

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:44.000
one of the engineering, aviation engineering unit.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And with the same setup, basically, structure.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:56.000
The first Sergeant had been, was told by a public exec, that he's hurt,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:03.000
that there was an announcement for, application of Officer Candidate School.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And that fellow back to I understand was an aviation cadet.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
He might be interested.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
But at that time, I had become the first Sergeant's clerk.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
How did I become his clerk?

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
One very wet day.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
The first Sergeant came out and said, okay.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.000
I need a clerk.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.000
I need a volunteer.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Who can type?

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
I had typing as a club from a hand up.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Okay, come here.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
Let's go in.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
Went into the first Sergeant's office.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.000
I found out that the first Sergeant had a little problem.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:45.000
My job was to read the company roster to him, the company roster,

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
because he could not read.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And he had it memorized, basically.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
He would get up in front of the company and put that paper up and call the role.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:57.000
That's a fewer reading.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
That's the kind of Army we had at that time.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And because I was able to type and help him, you're my clerk.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
Yes, first Sergeant.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
And when his lieutenant came back from post, he said, there's a roster.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:19.000
There's a campaign or statement on a board, vote and board at post,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
that it could be an Officer Candidate School application board.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
You might, be sure it might be interested.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:32.000
First Sergeant came in and said, you're going to go down and take a test.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
You're going to go down and appear at board.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
Yes, first Sergeant.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
I went down.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And this is one of the weird things.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:48.000
The President of the board had been through the township of Lower Merion.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And when I mentioned that I had gone to Lower Merion, played football there,

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
I had at least one person on my side.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:02.000
I didn't do poorly, but that made me feel pretty good when I was trying to answer the questions.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:08.000
That's how I started my process out of Keesler Field, out of Baluxy,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
out of McDill Field.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And I passed the Officer Candidate School test, passed the board.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And in January of 45, I went off to Fort Benning, GA, infantry Officer Candidate School.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
I got there in these semis, in fact, in 1944.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
School started in January of 45.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And I graduated from Officer Candidate School in August of 45.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
15 August in meanwhile.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:54.000
In the interesting part, they had dropped a bomb.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:58.000
We were destined to go off to become infantry lieutenants.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And meanwhile, when Germany quit about April of 45,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
we started getting concerned because, hey, they might cut off Officer Candidate School,

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
and there was no job.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
We were on key Officer Candidate School going.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
As a result, when the Japanese dropped it, they said, well, we're just close.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
They wouldn't there cut out Officer Candidate School now.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:30.000
They didn't, and we graduated on 16 August of 45.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:40.000
I was sent off briefly to Alabama from basic training, duty.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:46.000
And within three weeks, I was off to Pacific.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Well, yeah.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Now, Officer Candidate School is sort of a quirk.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
Officer Candidate School is not, we're not segregated, correct?

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
No, Officer Kennedy School.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Right.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:56.000
And they had Officer Kennedy School.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And it's designed to fill these void when they drop off sufficient,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
not going to the official officers coming out of West Point,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:09.000
or ROTCs, and there's still a need for more officers,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
Officer Kennedy School to group that they turned to.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.000
Right.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And that was an integrated.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:15.000
That was integrated.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:16.000
Yeah.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.000
Yeah.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
When I got there, integrated to a point.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
You always have to make sure that you're clear.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.000
I got inside the Officer Kennedy Regiment.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
We were just like everyone on every other soldier.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
Our training, we lived in integrated billets.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
We can integrate everything.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
However, you step outside of that regiment ever.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
You're back to the south.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
You waited in your line to get on a certain bus.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Even there going to the theater, outside the region area.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:57.000
You set a different location in your fellow candidates.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:02.000
But inside the training itself, completely integrated.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
And were there service clubs on the base?

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
Yes, service clubs in the base.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
But we went to a black service club.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And my white counterparts went to the white service club.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
Same thing for the Officer, Officer Club.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:21.000
And it was the southern way of doing business.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Okay.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So what then off to the Pacific?

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Off to the Pacific, joined a 93rd Infantry Division.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:34.000
All black divisions except for the division commander and his T-staff.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
One of the more interesting parts about that.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.000
We would overseas on a, well fortunately back up a little bit.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:54.000
Before leaving the States, I went to a place staging area in California.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
And I'm grouping now for the name of it.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:02.000
But it was the place to go from that staging area overseas.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:07.000
I met a couple of, or about 15 of us officers.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.000
Two of them were Westponders.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:18.000
And we became very good friends while we're in route to the Pacific.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:24.000
So much so that they convinced me doing our transit.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
If I ever had chance to go to Westpoint, I wouldn't do it.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Or I had my commission.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And I was not about to go through what they had to go through.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:35.000
The sourcing treatment and the other things.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.000
They also taught me how to shoot crap.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
They took my money because they taught me how to shoot crap on a blanket.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:45.000
If you know anything about shooting crap, that's the last thing you want to do.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
And they took my money from that.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
And I reminded them of that later when I had a chance.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Went off to the Pacific.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:55.000
The war just over.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:00.000
But there still were, I went to a place called Morotai, which is Southfoot,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
the Philippine, North of New Guinea.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
There were two divisions on Morotai.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
The 93rd Division and the Dixie Division.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
Why the Army put those two divisions together?

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:11.000
I'll never know.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
I tried to find out since then.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:16.000
No one has given me a satisfactory answer.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:22.000
But during the fighting, they did very well against the bad guy, the Japanese.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Keeped his mind as a war not going on.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
We're fighting the Japanese.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:33.000
When there were no fighting going on with the Japanese, they fought each other.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:38.000
So much so that I was pulled out of my regiment.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:44.000
I was in C Company, first battalion, three-sixth in Infantry,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:54.000
and sent on detail to the Provost Marshal and the Dixie Division had a lieutenant come up,

00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:02.000
and we rode patrols together to try to make sure maintain a little bit of peace.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
Peace between the two.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
Keep in mind, I was 19-year-old, second lieutenant.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:12.000
This guy from Dixie Division, the same age I was, so we were two characters stuck out there.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.000
Driving around in a Jeep.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
To drive around and keep peace.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Another interesting situation.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:20.000
The Dixie Division flying Confederate flags and all your things like this.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:27.000
Confederate flag as well, regimental flag.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:36.000
One of my combat activities was required to take a patrol into the hills,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:40.000
and the new to Japanese were someplace up in the hills, up in the mountain.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.000
The war was over, so we had Japanese translator.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:48.000
We went out, I had my platoon.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:54.000
The Japanese translator had a bullhorn, announcing the fact that war is over, give up,

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.000
come on, we'll take care of you.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:01.000
For that, we got shot at, and we were told not to engage.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
We had weapons to protect ourselves, but do not engage.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:10.000
We got shot at, we knew where they were, came back, report that to the battalion commander.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:17.000
He in turn reports that the regiment commander said, hey, no, the New York commander said,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:21.000
they're up there, we know where they are, we'll just start them out.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:27.000
That took her my first combat experience being shot at.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:39.000
That went on for time to deactivate the division, January of 46.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:46.000
If you had a certain number of quality points, or overseas points, you came home.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.000
I did not have any of those things, I just got in there.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:55.000
I, in the field, felt the respect to the technical services.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:01.000
I went to Manila as a signal unit.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
I reported in company.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:13.000
There were six officers, company commanders are captain.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:21.000
I went to junior, Lieutenant of the Chemical Command was an infantry officer.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:27.000
The three officers were signal officers, and rest of them were infantry.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:34.000
This is a heavy construction company, the kind of company that goes out and put them overhead wire and cable.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:41.000
Jolder holes in the ground, put into holes, and then string cable.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:47.000
I never drilled, I never been in a signal unit before, but one very much difficult.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
I knew what I had to do.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:54.000
I had a platoon of 30 odd soldiers.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:03.000
All of them were signal officers, signal soldiers, and they were happy to get a youngster in that could help them with many things.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:10.000
So they taught me how to climb holes, how to go up there, hang wire.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:15.000
We drilled a lot, I taught them how to do that.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
I did something the other lieutenants would not do.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
I climbed a pole and checked it out.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:31.000
We had a chance on one occasion to put in poles for, we're talking now Manila for radio or commercial.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.000
Radio of televisions too.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:36.000
We put in 100 foot poles.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:41.000
You put in 100 foot poles, you got about 10 feet into the ground.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:47.000
Once you get the pole to ground, now you have to go up and hang the wire.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:51.000
I didn't have much choice to go up or stay down.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:55.000
My soldier up hanging wire, I'm going to climb a pole too.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:58.000
I have never, I don't like heights.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:02.000
I got up that pole, went to the top of it.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:06.000
Sold what they were doing and came back down.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:14.000
Now, if you know anything about pole climbing, pole climbing, if you do 10 to 4 or slip,

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
the last thing you want to do is grab.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:23.000
You push yourself away from the pole and you have gaps on your feet and shoes,

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:28.000
which forces you fit into the pole and keeps you from falling.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:32.000
My other lieutenant wouldn't go up.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:36.000
My part too was so happy, moving to the company, he said, my lieutenant does that.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
Look at him.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:43.000
Well, I went up once, have not been up that high again on the pole.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
What I proved I could do it.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.000
And that's the way we operated.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:57.000
The company commander, as I said, was an infantry captain who later ran across in other services.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:03.000
My tour there ended when I was reached at going home,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:14.000
separated in 46, came home, went to,

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:19.000
I stayed in reserves, although I could have been separated.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:23.000
If I just felt like what I was doing, I stayed in reserves.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:30.000
In order to do that, I had to become a signal officer because I was infantry transferred to signal corps,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:37.000
doing an assignment, and when the reserve went into signal officer.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:43.000
State acted in the reserves and went to reserve training.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
I had a chance to go to college.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
Mine you had no college at this time.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:53.000
I had a role in Lincoln University, Lincoln College, excuse me.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:25:02.000
And at the week that I was supposed to report for class, which would have been in February of 47,

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:06.000
I got a call from my whole football coach, Laura Marion.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
How would you like to go to Muhlenberg College?

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
We're in the health Muhlenberg College.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
So now in town, Pennsylvania, why Muhlenberg College?

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.000
They got an excellent pre-med program.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:20.000
I went to the doctor at that time, and I said, hmm, okay.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
Sure.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:26.000
And so I went to Muhlenberg College College.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:29.000
At first, black American had gone to Muhlenberg College.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:36.000
I was on a football scholarship, and I used to collect about $38 a month stipend.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:40.000
We still care of my internals.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:48.000
So you, so rather than go to Lincoln, which is next BCU, maybe the first thing to see you.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
I went to Muhlenberg College.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:56.000
In Allentown, for black student, did very well as a matter of fact.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
How were, let me back up a little bit.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:06.000
Muhlenberg College, this is, I went there in February of 57, excuse me, 47.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
And the coach at Muhlenberg College had just gotten there.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:16.000
He came from a prep program, prep school, and he brought a couple of the old players,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:19.000
and they were really good players.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:25.000
He had spring practice, and we're out there under the lights, spring practice, contact.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:30.000
You know, injured myself, my shoulders, part of the reason I injured myself,

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and how it happened, my equipment was not properly fitted.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:41.000
The trainers who gave me equipment, that gave me inappropriate equipment,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:45.000
and I suffered shoulder separation.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
They purposely gave that to you.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:52.000
I also understand, that's why I ended up getting it, this is what it went.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:56.000
And I couldn't play football anymore.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:03.000
And I decided then that I really don't need this because I was doing quite well academically.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:08.000
And I found out that I could stay in college.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:11.000
I was there on the GI Bill of Rights, so I didn't need to, Monday for that standpoint.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:16.000
I didn't need to $30, $31 for stip for insininels.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:23.000
So I just dropped my scholarship, football scholarship, and got a series of upplaying academics.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:29.000
Of course, I forgot to mention, between the time I got home, they went to Muhlenberg,

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:34.000
I met a young nurse from Severnfield, of the Uofia.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:41.000
She was in nursing training, and we decided to get married.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:50.000
So in 48, January of 48, 29th of January, 48, we had our wedding.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:58.000
I'll point out that morning, day before that, I had taken a final exam in analytic geometry.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:05.000
I'm a pre-med student, and I did not do well.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:13.000
As a matter of fact, I went into that test, I read the questions, re-read them.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:19.000
In my answer on the street, I wrote down, re-wrote the question, and took a guess on each question,

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:24.000
and turned in, and the professors called me and said,

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:29.000
you know you didn't do well.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:33.000
Yes, sir. I know exactly what you've done.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:38.000
You have been memorizing formulas, analytic geometry, and he's right.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:43.000
I'd been memorizing, not understanding it.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
Up until that time, I'd been doing quite well.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:49.000
He said, okay, you've been making A's, but I'm going to give you a B,

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:53.000
but of course, because you've flown the final exam.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.000
Yes, sir. I understand that.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.000
The very next day I had my wedding.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:02.000
And a lot of friends say, I know you've flown the test.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:04.000
You're getting married.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.000
So that makes a long story short.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:14.000
We got married in 29th of January, and started off on our honeymoon,

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:17.000
and on, we just had a great time.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:22.000
I might add to honor honeymoon, which is a rather unique story.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:28.000
My brother, who, younger than I, but had dropped out of school during World War II,

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:35.000
joined the Navy, frustrated his parents, and everyone else.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.000
But he had dropped, he ran away from home a couple of times,

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:43.000
so mom was convinced that he would not do well staying there.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.000
So he went to join the Navy.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
She approved him to join the Navy.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:50.000
And he went off going off to college.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:57.000
And he was going to college and show you the rest of you in North Carolina.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:01.000
To get down there, we were driving down.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:07.000
And so my mother drove the car, and my brother Joe, my wife Louise,

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:08.000
and I went down.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:09.000
A unique story.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:15.000
Your mother going on your honeymoon, but that's the way we operate in those days.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:22.000
And dropped the more, came back up, and everything went fine from then.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:34.000
But that was in January of 48.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.000
State did quite well in school.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:47.000
Harry Truman, later that year, issued the executive order 9981 to integrate the military.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:52.000
I really had enjoyed being in the military, and I was in training camp

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:58.000
that everything improving ground during the summer when the order was issued.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:03.000
And I came back home and told my wife, well, I'll have a chance to go back to the actor duty.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:06.000
And I really liked what I was doing.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
And I could not be a doctor any hell.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:14.000
I wasn't doing well in chemistry, which not very good for a doctor.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:18.000
So she was happy to satisfy with because she was a nurse working.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.000
So we weren't going to starve.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
While I was at Aberdeen Proving Ground Proving Ground when the order was issued,

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:30.000
the commander of the post called all the officers together.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:35.000
He read the executive order signed by the president.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:40.000
And after he finished, and Aberdeen Proving Ground body was a completely integrated post,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
read the executive order.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.000
He called the duty officer.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:48.000
And he said, as long as I'm here, there'd be no change.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:52.000
And by that, he meant officer club number one, officer club number two.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:56.000
Swimming pool number one, swim pool number two, NCO club number one, NCO club number two.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:59.000
All the ones are white, all the two are black.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:05.000
And doing his very, as the commander, after the orders issued, no change.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:14.000
So when I went back on act of duty, we were expecting our first child.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:25.000
I was now at, I was on orders to a signal unit, signal unit at Fort Bliss Texas.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:33.000
I was recalled as an infantry officer because I wanted to go to infantry.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
Part of my interruption, but I just wanted to follow up.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:42.000
Having heard the president's executive order,

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:51.000
and I imagine having some reaction to that and hope for a career possibility is opening up.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.000
And then hearing the response of the commander, the post commander,

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.000
can you walk me through the range of feelings that you went through?

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:03.000
Well, let me back up a little bit of history.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:07.000
World War I.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:14.000
The black soldiers were fighting in segregated units.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:20.000
The commander and Europe, parsing did not want black troops.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:24.000
Black Command.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:34.000
So, $369 by unit in World War II had fought with the French because they preferred, they wanted us.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:36.000
And it will.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:41.000
Came back well rewarded.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:45.000
And when a $369 got back in the States, they were not greeted as heroes,

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:49.000
but they came back through New York and jeered.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:54.000
In 1925, I could be off by a year.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:59.000
There was a study done at Carlisle Barracks, the Army War College,

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:06.000
basically saying that the black soldiers, while they may be good,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:09.000
doing steeper-daw work,

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:14.000
laboring, they were not good for

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:22.000
thinking through a project or being able to officially control soldiers

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:26.000
and could not do certain other things, technical things.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:29.000
That study stayed around for a long time.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:35.000
So, when World War II came along, that was the mentality of the officer corps,

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.000
of leadership, of the war department.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:40.000
There was no reason to change it.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:45.000
When Gen. Benjamin O. Davis Jr became a fighter pilot, he had some major problems,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:51.000
but because in 1993, the 99th Pursuit Squadron did very well.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
We were able to shoot down aircraft and not lost any aircraft,

00:34:54.000 --> 00:35:00.000
not lost a fighter that day were escorting, or a permanent escorting.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:05.000
So, it didn't surprise me or anyone else that there were certain beliefs

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.000
in the military, leaders that, not just the president, that we can do,

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.000
this is our Army, and we're gonna do what we wanna do.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:18.000
May I point out today in 2015,

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:21.000
you have attitudes where folks are saying one thing,

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.000
and the president is saying something else?

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.000
It's not much different.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:30.000
So, the Army, soldiers and leaders are doing what they're told to do,

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:34.000
and once the word came out, and it set the mind to do certain things,

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:37.000
to get on with the program.

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:40.000
Their job is to be loyal.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:46.000
And no one contested that I know of this post commander.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:51.000
I'm not too sure that the Army, what department knew about it?

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.000
I'm a lieutenant, I'm not gonna get up there and challenge it,

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:57.000
no one else would have challenged it, so.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:02.000
I left that post, by the way, when I'm ahead of myself now,

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:09.000
but what he had it to was, when.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
In the executive order didn't have a timeline, it just.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:13.000
No, yeah, yeah.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:21.000
It basically said, as I recall,

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.000
I can look at that book over here,

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:29.000
I got the order in there, but basically said,

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
we've all delivered speed.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:35.000
Very similar to the brand decision, all delivered speed.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:42.000
And so, I'm now back on Acta-Duty,

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:48.000
went to Fort Bliss as a signal officer.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:56.000
I had applied for infantry, and I had applied to become a regular Army officer.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
The difference between being a regular Army officer and a reserve officer is,

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
I hope, it's understood.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:07.000
It's a way to go if you're gonna be a career soldier.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:13.000
Well, I Fort Bliss, I was in a signal unit company.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:16.000
I was a junior officer,

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:25.000
and our job was to go from Fort Bliss to Fort Bragg,

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:31.000
and participate in a maneuvers.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
To do this, you got to drive by road,

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.000
and we took our signal unit, trucks and all,

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.000
from Fort Bliss to Fort Bragg,

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.000
and as I said, I'm the junior officer,

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:47.000
so I'm the guy in charge of the Messhall kitchen.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:52.000
My job with the book of cooks took a while, cooked,

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
and when the soldiers joined us,

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:57.000
feed them, and then move to the next point,

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:01.000
while they're coming along behind us, cook, prepare a meal for them,

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.000
select a bib like area.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:11.000
Driving by road from El Paso to Fort Bragg,

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:14.000
it's not easily done.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
We don't have your radio communication.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
We're signal unit, but we don't do a radio,

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:21.000
which is telephone.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:29.000
The very first place out, Van Horn, Texas,

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:32.000
very unique place.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:35.000
They didn't cut into blocks at all,

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.000
no matter where an army or not.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:42.000
It so happened that I had a,

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:46.000
I'd going out, set up our bill of act area,

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:48.000
set up the kitchen,

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.000
did a cooking, when the company came in,

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:55.000
then I had to take a listing of things,

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:58.000
one thing wanted from downtown.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
Okay, that's easy.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.000
I took a list of things they wanted,

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:05.000
of course, soldiers want things that don't provide,

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:10.000
like cigarettes, candy, and you name it,

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
I had a list.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:15.000
I went down to a local drug store

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:21.000
and I gave a list to the store owner,

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.000
and he was happy,

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:26.000
he was gripping a list of things he could sell.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.000
And you're in uniform?

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.000
I was in uniform, I clearly feel uniform.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:32.000
I went to the fountain,

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
sort of fountain,

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:35.000
where they make ice cream,

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:36.000
and stuff like that.

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.000
I often join myself,

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
and my sergeant who would be

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.000
was collecting things that we were going to buy.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:47.000
All of a sudden, the guy behind the counter,

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:48.000
stiffened up,

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.000
I had a paint shirt,

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
and the next thing they got,

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:53.000
a chap me on the shoulder,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:54.000
get away from the counter.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:55.000
Why?

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:56.000
I said so.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:57.000
I turned around,

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:58.000
gripping bad chair,

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.000
and a great big fellow in uniform with a weapon.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:03.000
And,

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
okay,

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
I understood what he was saying,

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
and I understood why he said it.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:10.000
And I said to the sergeant,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.000
have we paid for anything yet?

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:13.000
No sir.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
Okay, we're leaving.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.000
And we walked out.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:22.000
And the sheriff had gotten back to the bid bike area,

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:25.000
by the way, I forgot to mention my company commander was a major white.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:28.000
He got back to the bid bike area,

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:32.000
and the sheriff had gotten there before I got there.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:35.000
And he had told this,

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:36.000
the sheriff would tell him,

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:39.000
this major that this boy you got over here,

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:42.000
doesn't understand what goes on down here.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:43.000
The major said,

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:44.000
that boy is a lieutenant,

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:45.000
he's not from here.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
He's doing what I told him to do.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:48.000
And he said,

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:51.000
he better tell him something differently while he's here.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Okay?

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:54.000
Sheriff left.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:55.000
I get back.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
I told what took place.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
The very next morning,

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:00.000
we're heading out,

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:04.000
continuing our route.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:07.000
And a sedan,

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:08.000
stood a baker,

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:09.000
as a matter of fact,

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
had an accident.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:15.000
It passed us flying like a bad out of hell.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:16.000
And I had, by the way,

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:18.000
a Jeep and a three-quarter tonne,

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:23.000
just called pickup truck type thing.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:25.000
He passed us like a bad out of hell,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
had an accident,

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:29.000
a clover.

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:34.000
And we get up there to where it was,

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
so what happened?

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:39.000
Took the emergency rounds,

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.000
we took the two women

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:43.000
out of the truck,

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:45.000
out of the cars,

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:47.000
pulling up pickup truck,

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.000
and I continued in my Jeep,

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:52.000
on my way,

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:57.000
my truck took the women back to the hospital in Van Horn, Texas.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:03.000
The doctors said that the action of these soldiers

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.000
saved these women.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:08.000
And when the sheriff came into the hospital

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:11.000
to hear what the accident started,

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:12.000
checking on,

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:14.000
wondering, okay, how did it happen?

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:16.000
Who brought them back?

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:17.000
And my sergeant,

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:19.000
who had whipped me the night before,

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:20.000
that lieutenant,

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:21.000
who you chased out of town

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:24.000
to wanted to save these women lives.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:27.000
There was a message there too.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
We went on our way from there on time,

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:32.000
that on to Fort Bragg.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:35.000
But that was a unique experience for me,

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:36.000
to go through that.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.000
It changed the minds of some people too,

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.000
to include that sheriff.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:45.000
Hey, maybe it's not all bad for these soldiers.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:50.000
That went on until we went to,

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:55.000
we got to Fort Bragg,

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:56.000
went through the drill,

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:01.000
putting in communications.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.000
It was shortly thereafter,

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:05.000
my orders came through,

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
my assignment came through

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:11.000
to go to a infantry unit.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:20.000
And I was then transferred from the 29th signal to

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:27.000
the second division at Fort Lewis,

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:30.000
on competitive tour,

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
competing for a regular army appointment.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:40.000
And we did quite well at Fort Lewis,

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:43.000
still a segregated unit.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.000
The division,

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.000
9th infantry regiment,

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
had three battalions.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.000
One battalion was black,

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:55.000
yellow to battalion were white.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:44:01.000
I was assigned to

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:04.000
the first battalion in the

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:07.000
United States,

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.000
ill company,

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
third battalion,

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
ninth infantry.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:17.000
We trained and were prepared to

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:20.000
keep going we're doing.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:22.000
And the Korean War broke out.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:25.000
So I was just asking about the facilities.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:26.000
Right, at Fort Lewis.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:27.000
Ready to go again?

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:28.000
Yes, we're going.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:29.000
At Fort Lewis,

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:33.000
we had a very big complement of three regiments.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:36.000
And the only regiment that had blacks were

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
in ninth infantry.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:40.000
The other two regiment did not.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:45.000
And the division artillery had a black battalion.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
The black battalion in the ninth infantry,

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
the third battalion,

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:53.000
as I said, was all black except for the battalion command

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:54.000
with black two.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.000
Another story about that.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.000
The battalion,

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:00.000
one of the sergeants,

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.000
turned out to be a pretty important person.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
He became a member of the Congress,

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:05.000
Charles B. Rangel.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
That name, Charles B. Rangel.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:08.000
Yes, it does.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:10.000
He was from the battalion,

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:11.000
and we talked about this many times,

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.000
it's that time.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:19.000
But when,

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.000
as I said, we trained very hard,

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:25.000
trained very hard at Fort Lewis before the war broke out.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:29.000
I was among my regular duties of infantry,

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:33.000
and I was also in charge of the battalion later became

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:36.000
the regimental drill team.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:40.000
And we had a tremendously fine unit.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:42.000
We're not put on performances,

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:43.000
not only for soldier,

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
but also for civilians.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:48.000
They did quite well.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:51.000
And I got quite a reputation for doing that.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:53.000
And your equipment was up to date?

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.000
The equipment was up to date, everything.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:57.000
It was like the rest of the unit,

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.000
the rest of the army, but we're still black,

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:01.000
ourselves.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:05.000
I asked for the battalion commander,

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
he said, go ahead and do it.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:09.000
I said, let's, we got some soldiers, white soldiers,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:13.000
from the rest of the regiment wanted to join our team.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
I was happy with that.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:18.000
But I had to go to regimental exec.

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:21.000
And I'll never forget what he said.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:24.000
So I like the way your team, what they do.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:27.000
They look good, and a good for the army,

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:29.000
and certainly good for the soldier.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:31.000
But we put white soldiers in there,

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:35.000
they'll break up the parents in the color.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:38.000
Lieutenant Colonel saying that, I'm a lieutenant.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:39.000
How much I could say about that?

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:41.000
Okay, fine.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:47.000
Yet, again, we're talking 19 and 50.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:53.000
We trained, and right by the time when the,

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:59.000
in April of 1950, our battalion commander got orders

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:05.000
to go to, to be reassigned.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:09.000
And it was the war broke out as you may recall,

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:13.000
in June of 50.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
And he had just,

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:19.000
still in the post, but not moved.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:21.000
And when the word came out that we got to be,

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:24.000
we're going to be sent overseas, alerted for war,

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:26.000
for combat.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:29.000
We had white battalion commander in, in, now.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:34.000
And we thought that the army could do the right thing,

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:36.000
bring our battalion commander back,

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.000
who we have before, who would train us,

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.000
did a very fine job doing that,

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.000
and put it back, put us,

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:46.000
with our old commander.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.000
He was the only lieutenant Colonel,

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:51.000
the I knew of, they had a PhD.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:54.000
He had to be a,

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:57.000
a suology biologist,

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:58.000
and doing it.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.000
He was also a very hard-knosed person,

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
for demanding excellence,

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
and he'll fire you in a heartbeat,

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:06.000
and, of course, he made your problem.

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:10.000
But we're pleased with that, because we knew that he was on our side.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:13.000
The person he brought back in to command,

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:16.000
with the commander that we had before he got there,

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.000
he was still doing something else.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:19.000
And a lot of us thought that,

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.000
hey, bring back our commander,

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
because he done so well.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:27.000
He didn't work that way.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.000
Now, June of,

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:32.000
we're deployed, 1950,

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:34.000
the night infantry,

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:37.000
with the first unit to leave the states,

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:40.000
to go to Korea.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:43.000
Did you know where you were going?

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:44.000
We know it was Korea,

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.000
did you know anything about Korea?

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:47.000
No, no.

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:49.000
I didn't know where Korea was.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:50.000
Hey, I'm on.

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:51.000
I'm now 19.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:54.000
I guess I'm about 20 by that time.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:56.000
But I quickly found out where it was,

00:48:56.000 --> 00:48:57.000
and what they were doing.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
I knew what had to do with what he got there,

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.000
to be prepared to fight.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:05.000
And we were on board ships,

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:08.000
heading off to the combat zone,

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:14.000
landed at Pusan Perimeter.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:19.000
My unit was the,

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:23.000
elk coming with the first to land,

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:29.000
went into a big white area,

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:32.000
water rest of the battalion,

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:35.000
and regiment came on.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
And rest of the enough,

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:40.000
while we're setting there,

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:43.000
we got work that we're going to be removed from the regiment

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:46.000
on a separate mission.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:49.000
This is 1950,

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
and no one asked the question,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.000
why I've been going to the (Gen.) MacArthur headquarters,

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
(Gen. Douglas) MacArthur's headquarters,

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
I want to battalion to go up,

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
to Pohang,

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:02.000
to protect an airfield.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Okay.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:09.000
So, as we were getting our gear ready,

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:13.000
I got called to regiment headquarters.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:18.000
Lieutenant Becton, we want you to take a patrol

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:22.000
with communication gear to set up a command,

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:24.000
a command post,

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:27.000
CP communication rather,

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:28.000
when we closed in,

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.000
when your battalion closed into it,

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.000
I'll never ready to go.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:38.000
And so, I got my sufficient number of men,

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:41.000
a small platoon,

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:44.000
and took communication gear,

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:47.000
a couple of three,

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
pick up, three,

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:50.000
two and a half ton truck

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
with communication gear and a vacuum.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:55.000
And we drove from our airfield

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:58.000
to the site where we were sent to protect an airfield,

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:01.000
protect an airfield.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.000
And we got there,

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:06.000
I asked the question,

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:07.000
by the way,

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
any activity in the area?

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:13.000
No, no one, no bad guys there.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.000
And we got up to Pohang Gang,

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
set up a command,

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
our gear,

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:22.000
and as we did that morning,

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.000
we're waiting for the battalion to join us,

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
and we got reported in that the battalion got ambushed,

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
and lost some people,

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:36.000
and they finally joined the area of which we were in,

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.000
the same area that we had driven through,

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:43.000
and the guys at Bedgah knew who we were,

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:45.000
they could have done serious damage,

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
but let us go through,

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
they could take our big, bigger thing later.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
When we came up,

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
we didn't got ambushed,

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.000
and we survived that,

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:59.000
my first close call.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:02.000
We stayed there,

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:05.000
had a couple patrols,

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:08.000
protect an airfield,

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:10.000
and then the orders came in

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:13.000
for the battalion to move back and join the regiment.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:22.000
It is now September.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:25.000
We're breaking out of the effort,

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:28.000
we're now to break out a Pohang perimeter,

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.000
which has some notoriety

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:34.000
that the forces were driven back into that.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:40.000
And we rejoined the regiment,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:43.000
and prepared to go to the serious combat.

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:48.000
We've had some combat up until that time.

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:51.000
The Ella Company was to be the lead,

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:54.000
a battalion,

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:57.000
the company battalion,

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:02.000
after we had joined the regiment.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:05.000
My platoon got selected to be the lead,

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:08.000
to be in the company.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:12.000
And as we were moving out,

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:16.000
with all of our armor

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.000
and everything else,

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.000
ran into a attacking hill call,

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:23.000
201.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:26.000
This hill was well protected.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:29.000
We got half way up the hill,

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:34.000
and we got ran to a tremendous enemy fire,

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:37.000
and had to protect ourselves

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:39.000
and seek cover.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:42.000
And while we're there,

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:45.000
the adjacent battalion,

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.000
second battalion, engaged up,

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
because no one had told them

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
that US forces could be out there,

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
one of those crazy things.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.000
So the bad guys are fighting at us,

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:58.000
our battalion is firing at us,

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:00.000
and we had nothing to do,

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:04.000
but hunker down until we could night-kame.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:07.000
We returned a fire on the bad guys,

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:10.000
and prayed that we were able to do

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.000
some damage on the bad guys,

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
but we got hurt.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:16.000
When darkness came,

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:20.000
we withdrew back into the battalion area.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.000
I had lost some people,

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:25.000
but we brought them with us.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:28.000
But that breakthrough was sufficient

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:31.000
enough for our battalion to move out.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:38.000
I might add that while we're in this also battle,

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:43.000
we had support by our Air Force.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:49.000
And they took us for enemy.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:52.000
So they also attacked us too,

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.000
firing a aircraft.

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:56.000
And no matter what we did,

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:59.000
they kept going on some of my messenger of mine

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.000
as a lieutenant now.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:06.000
He grabbed a panel of marking panels,

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:09.000
and he got out in front and weaved them up and down to Air Force,

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.000
and we're coming back at us.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.000
They understood that wrong hill,

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
get the next hill.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.000
We got him on war by the way for that.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:21.000
And he probably saved our lives.

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.000
The interesting part about that,

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:27.000
I had told my men that once we were getting combat,

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:30.000
we're going to step to here as a team.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:32.000
Don't start running to the rear.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:34.000
If you do, I'll kill you.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:37.000
It's talking cheek-day thought.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:42.000
And when the plane came back,

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:46.000
some of my soldiers start to get up and shoot.

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:49.000
I'm going to run, move back to the rear.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:53.000
And I took a carbine, a small rifle,

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:56.000
an unloader magazine in front of them.

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:58.000
And they looked at me and looked at the planes.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:02.000
And they knew that I was closer to them than the planes.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
And they got back on the ground.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:07.000
In the meantime, the soldiers, the fighter pilots,

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:10.000
also recognized that we're good guys.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:14.000
And so they went elsewhere.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:16.000
My soldiers got back on the ground,

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:22.000
and when we got back in the camp, recovered,

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:24.000
we had a little discussion.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:26.000
Lieutenant, would you have shot us?

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:28.000
You're here, aren't you?

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:31.000
Well, yeah, you didn't keep running, did you?

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:34.000
No. Well, you make up your own mind.

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:42.000
It was also doing that period that I had gotten wounded.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:45.000
And that was my first trip to the hospital.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:49.000
I went back to Japan, as a matter of fact,

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:54.000
in up in Sendai, Japan for my recovery.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:58.000
And I'm pulling that out because I came back

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:01.000
to join a unit as soon as I could,

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:02.000
because General MacArthur said,

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:04.000
we're going to be home for Christmas.

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
And I want to be back at victory.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:10.000
We're going to be home for Christmas.

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
I didn't work out that way.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:16.000
I rejoined the regiment from the hospital.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:19.000
And by that time, the regiment did a very good job.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:20.000
It was done quite well.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:24.000
We had moved north, in the North Korea.

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:30.000
And I was in the Natalia, the Natalia, 9th Infantry.

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:36.000
And one of the lead regiments in the attack going up north.

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:44.000
And once again, my company was selected to lead the battalion.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:47.000
And it was cold, then.

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:51.000
Remember, we left the states in summertime.

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:54.000
We didn't have winter gear.

00:57:54.000 --> 00:58:00.000
And we're now up north of the 38th parallel into North Korea.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:05.000
Not too many miles from the northern border.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:09.000
Again, we had our battles to do.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:12.000
And it's mountainous, and it's cold.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:13.000
It is, right?

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:15.000
And no winter gear.

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:20.000
But we were able to take care of ourselves.

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:29.000
We're now in November.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:38.000
It's cold, digging in to fight, to continue to fight going north.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:41.000
It was Thanksgiving time.

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:44.000
And I remember that, the coup, the Turkic dinner.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:48.000
However, by the time the Mito got where we were,

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:52.000
the Turk was a little bit cold, like frozen.

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:56.000
And we found we take care of that, our kids and the best they could.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:59:03.000
And we had dug in, had our fires out, trying to stay warm.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:06.000
And the Chinese entered the war.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:11.000
The date you can check that, find what, because it was very specific when they came in.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:18.000
We contained the battle against the Chinese and the North Koreans.

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:26.000
I was, again, my particular pick to lead the company in the attack.

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:35.000
Again, we were told to record order a ground high ground in front of us.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:41.000
Would you ever wonder why you kept getting chosen to lead?

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:47.000
Did you ever wonder why your unit kept getting chosen to go out front?

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:49.000
We were pretty good at it.

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:50.000
Yeah.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
And remember, I said I was on competitive to the tour.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
I was competing for regular army appointments.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:57.000
So the battalion commander, even Ubatan commander, said, OK,

00:59:57.000 --> 00:59:59.000
vectors can make it happen.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:02.000
We're the only guy who can do the same thing, but no.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:08.000
And my company commander, who was a pretty good friend of my dad,

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:10.000
he had other looters he could pick on.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:14.000
But they had two of them have been in combat in World War II.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:19.000
And I'm now a 20-year-old, an eager and everything else.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:20.000
I had a good unit.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
We trained well.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:25.000
My soldiers trusted me and I trusted them.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:26.000
And I held.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:27.000
I was prepared to do it.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:28.000
You were ready.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:29.000
Yeah.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:34.000
The next time, we were making a tie-up a hill.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:43.000
And as I was before I left, my battalion commander had been approached by the

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:50.000
adjacent battalion commander from the 25th regiment, which happened to be a black unit

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:53.000
too on the 25th division.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:02.000
And my battalion commander, we're collaborating, talking about many things, I guess.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:06.000
I'm heading up the hill, running the contact.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:14.000
And I was told, do not engage because you're out to buy yourself with your patrol

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:17.000
return to battalion.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:24.000
I came off the hill and reported the battalion commander and the other battalion commander,

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:25.000
there's nothing up there.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:27.000
I know better than that.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:30.000
And my car looked at me and looked back at him.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:33.000
And I got orders, okay, get back up there.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:37.000
And I start back up the hill again with my unit.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:39.000
This time picked up a wound.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:45.000
One of the military, a thousand dollar wound.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:52.000
The bullet went through between my tendon and my left ankle and the bone.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:56.000
It got the tendon nor did it touch the bone.

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:58.000
Now how much space is down there?

01:01:58.000 --> 01:01:59.000
Not much.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:01.000
The bullet went through there.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:04.000
Nothing, no damage done to either.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:06.000
I came back down.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.000
The battalion commander still there.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:11.000
Are you satisfied now, Colonel?

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:13.000
He wrong.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:18.000
I got evacuated from the battalion.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:24.000
That's when history would tell you that the army had his first defeat.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:32.000
When the Chinese and the North Korean attacked US forces and chased them out of North Korea.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:38.000
I got evacuated by air.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:43.000
The battalion and regiment suffered severe damage.

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:47.000
The final toll where I think is I recall,

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:52.000
another battalion, five officers survived.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:55.000
The elder had captured a kill.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:03.000
I fell into category one to five survived because I had been evacuated and now back in Japan.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:11.000
The US force pushed back south for the 38th Paranole and regrouped.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:17.000
I am now back in Japan, back to the same hospital I'd been in before, which I rushed out of.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:19.000
Went to the same war as a matter of fact.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.000
You?

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:22.000
Back here again?

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Yes, I'm back here again.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:27.000
In this time, I'm not going to rush home.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:28.000
They understood.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:31.000
I got very good treatment and care.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:39.000
During that period, the army regrouped, recovered, prepared to take care of business.

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:44.000
I was told to rebuild your strength by going out and learning how to ski.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:47.000
Send I known for its slopes and stuff like that.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:49.000
And so, flying, I've gone and tried.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:52.000
I never ski before you understand.

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:55.000
Went out to the training area where they teach skiing.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:04:03.000
And they gave me skis, flagboard, two straps, one across the insta, one across the hill.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
No boots, nothing else.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:09.000
And I did like you might expect you ski by the way.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:10.000
Yes.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:12.000
So you understand what kind of trouble I had.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:15.000
I did not do very well at all.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:20.000
But I managed to get back off the hill and went back to the hospital area.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:29.000
But that taught me a lesson about trying to ski with that kind of equipment.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:35.000
I eventually come back to the unit now in March, back to the regiment.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:41.000
And the back in the base camp before I moved up to the regiment.

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:46.000
They had a new executive officer in the regiment.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:50.000
Lieutenant Colonel Arlento, Marsani.

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:53.000
And you'll see why I remember that name in a few minutes.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:05:01.000
And when I get back to the regimental rear, and I meet the battalion exec,

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:05.000
he enroves me to this regimental exec.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:11.000
And the battalion execs said, we're going to put back to the battalion and become,

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:14.000
he'll put them into an S3 operation.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:18.000
He's been in combat, he understands he can help us there.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:20.000
Or a sign that would look at me.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:22.000
Lieutenant, how you feel?

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.000
I feel pretty good, sir.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:27.000
We're going to put them into a company.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:28.000
Why?

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:31.000
Because the company picked from me was L company.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:32.000
Sound familiar?

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:33.000
Company I was in, men and four.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:36.000
They had lost all of the officers and a few of the insurgents.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:39.000
They needed some leadership up there.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:42.000
Battalion agent said, but sir, he just got...

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:44.000
He's going to go to the company.

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:46.000
Yes, sir.

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:51.000
So I ended up going back to K company, L company, excuse me.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:53.000
And he's correct.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:56.000
We had all the officers been gone.

01:05:56.000 --> 01:05:58.000
We got lost.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:02.000
Somebody in the open had a couple of key insurgents that knew me and I knew them.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:05.000
So I'm now in the company commander.

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:09.000
And we organized what we had.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:12.000
We had gotten some new lieutenants, second lieutenants.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:16.000
Still all black or white replacements at this point.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:18.000
By that time we were integrated.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:19.000
I failed to mention one point.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:21.000
Let me go back a little bit.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:28.000
Back in August, before I got 201 when I got my first loan,

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:34.000
the regiment commander, Colonel Col. Col. Chin C. (or Cesidio C.?) Sloan,

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:39.000
had been told by the adjutant we got incoming replacements,

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:43.000
called for up by M.O.F. military operations,

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:47.000
military specialties, but not by race.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:49.000
And Sloan said, put them where they're needed.

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:51.000
Put them where they're needed.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:54.000
Dr. C. took care of the integration within the NIFE infantry.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:57.000
Went to the battalions, spread them out.

01:06:57.000 --> 01:07:03.000
And when I got my first integrated soldier, he was a...

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:09.000
American, Mexican American, from Texas.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:12.000
And when he came in, I told my patuist,

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:15.000
I don't let anything happen to that guy.

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:17.000
He's our first one non-blank.

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:19.000
We're not going to hurt him at all.

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:23.000
And he said, yes sir, we'll take care of that.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:25.000
And with that we became integrated.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:29.000
And so now the division integrated.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:32.000
And by the time we were in the fighting,

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:35.000
we had black company commanders and white battalions,

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:36.000
and so forth.

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:38.000
So we're doing quite well.

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:40.000
When I got back today...

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:43.000
It was military necessity that re-witching.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:45.000
It was military necessity.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:47.000
It was the need for bodies.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.000
Yeah, there's so forth in the house.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:52.000
It was...it had nothing to do with the executive order.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:57.000
The fact that we were combat, where people qualified,

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:00.000
and the commanders recognized their soldiers,

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:05.000
put them where they needed military necessity.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:08.000
And that's the way we operated.

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:11.000
By the time I got back to the regiment,

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:15.000
it would have been about...

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:20.000
I guess April, I can check my book for you to find out

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:22.000
what that time was.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:28.000
And we were in a base area.

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:33.000
The division was still engaged.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:36.000
I am now a company commander.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:40.000
Lieutenant, first lieutenant.

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:44.000
And we got a white officer, Captain, assigned to us

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:47.000
to be the company commander.

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:53.000
And he had not been in combat before.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:57.000
The company had completely integrated by this time.

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:01.000
Then we had low-and-discussive captain myself.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:03.000
And he said, okay.

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:06.000
I want you to keep doing what you've been doing to be in charge.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:10.000
I'll take care of the base area and support you.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:14.000
And that's all I finished to war in Korea.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:18.000
With that arrangement,

