02:07:23.000 --> 02:07:30.000
I think I mentioned that and we trained for very hard.

02:07:30.000 --> 02:07:32.000
And I enjoyed what I was doing.

02:07:32.000 --> 02:07:35.000
I had a good staff and good troops.

02:07:35.000 --> 02:07:39.000
Came over to Chief of Staffs office.

02:07:40.000 --> 02:07:53.000
I left there as Lieutenant Colonel rather important period because I went out to Campbell as a squadron commander in the 101st Airborne Division.

02:07:53.000 --> 02:08:02.000
Which is the, there are two Airborne Division, 82nd in the 101st.

02:08:03.000 --> 02:08:06.000
And we have to think that 101st is the best of them.

02:08:06.000 --> 02:08:18.000
And on top of that I was a Lieutenant Colonel, armor leaving the National War College going off to command a squadron.

02:08:18.000 --> 02:08:30.000
And the, there was only one Cav Squadron into the division.

02:08:31.000 --> 02:08:37.000
And only two Cav Squadrons like that in the Army, one 82nd the other 101st.

02:08:37.000 --> 02:08:40.000
And now it's time to, and we train very well, very hard.

02:08:40.000 --> 02:08:42.000
Now I'm not, I will not Airborne qualified.

02:08:42.000 --> 02:08:50.000
I got Airborne qualified when I left the, on a Forces staff car I went to jump school and qualified as a paratrooper.

02:08:50.000 --> 02:08:53.000
You remember I said when I'm gonna pull, I don't like heights.

02:08:53.000 --> 02:08:55.000
Why don't you jump out of airplane?

02:08:55.000 --> 02:08:58.000
He's a challenge, that's what I did.

02:08:58.000 --> 02:09:01.000
So you were continually training even through all these.

02:09:01.000 --> 02:09:02.000
That's right.

02:09:02.000 --> 02:09:04.000
Hey, that's what we're all about.

02:09:04.000 --> 02:09:07.000
But I'm now Airborne qualified.

02:09:07.000 --> 02:09:14.000
I'm gonna command a armor unit, I spent most of my time as infantry, except with the second Army Division.

02:09:14.000 --> 02:09:17.000
I was an armored infantry, but not an armored unit as such.

02:09:17.000 --> 02:09:19.000
Never command a tank unit.

02:09:19.000 --> 02:09:21.000
Never even fired a tank gun.

02:09:21.000 --> 02:09:24.000
But I go off to the 101st Airborne Division.

02:09:24.000 --> 02:09:30.000
We train hard, Vietnam.

02:09:30.000 --> 02:09:35.000
I am the only black commander in the division at that level.

02:09:35.000 --> 02:09:45.000
And all of the battalion commanders, we have one black Colonel, and he commanded the trains, logistics.

02:09:45.000 --> 02:09:52.000
We're off to Vietnam that very well.

02:09:53.000 --> 02:09:56.000
Battalion squadron commander for the first part of my tour.

02:09:56.000 --> 02:10:02.000
And then the last part of my tour was Deputy Brigade Commander.

02:10:02.000 --> 02:10:09.000
And I had chance to meet some very important people as a squadron commander.

02:10:09.000 --> 02:10:15.000
During the war, I got visited by fellow named Creighton Abrams.

02:10:15.000 --> 02:10:21.000
Military assistant commander, MACV and Vietnam.

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:25.000
I was the only armor unit in his area, in that area.

02:10:25.000 --> 02:10:28.000
And when he came out, he came to visit me.

02:10:28.000 --> 02:10:33.000
He landed his chopper, get out, salute him, come over, sit on the Jeep.

02:10:33.000 --> 02:10:35.000
Okay, Joyce, what have you done now?

02:10:35.000 --> 02:10:38.000
I'm talking to him about what we're doing, how well we're doing and so forth.

02:10:38.000 --> 02:10:45.000
Got a great relationship, which proved to be very important later on.

02:10:45.000 --> 02:10:52.000
Fort the war, we got a couple of citations, medals and stuff like that.

02:10:52.000 --> 02:11:12.000
Came back to the States, assigned to the Army staff again,

02:11:12.000 --> 02:11:18.000
as a colonel.

02:11:18.000 --> 02:11:31.000
I get promoted to Brigadier General and assigned to Fort Dix New Jersey.

02:11:31.000 --> 02:11:40.000
Now an interesting part about that, Fort Dix is not too far from Philadelphia.

02:11:40.000 --> 02:11:43.000
I'm now the deputy commander of Fort Dix.

02:11:43.000 --> 02:11:48.000
My job is to really be the guidance charge of training the post commanders

02:11:48.000 --> 02:11:50.000
and job to everything else.

02:11:50.000 --> 02:11:54.000
And we worked very hard, drill sergeant worked for me.

02:11:54.000 --> 02:11:59.000
And I had a superb boss.

02:11:59.000 --> 02:12:09.000
Early on, he sent me to Washington to convince the Army not to close Fort Dix.

02:12:09.000 --> 02:12:12.000
He was doing a phase down.

02:12:12.000 --> 02:12:17.000
And the folks in the Army determined to close it.

02:12:17.000 --> 02:12:23.000
And our article was, this is the major training center in the whole North-Eastern Puerto Rican

02:12:23.000 --> 02:12:24.000
United States.

02:12:24.000 --> 02:12:27.000
For a paracendera, youngsters to go in the Army and train there.

02:12:27.000 --> 02:12:29.000
Now you're going to close it.

02:12:29.000 --> 02:12:34.000
And I had beat up by Frank L. Rizzo from Philadelphia, mayor.

02:12:34.000 --> 02:12:38.000
He went on to tell the Fort they can't close it because we needed.

02:12:38.000 --> 02:12:41.000
All the time, my civilians who live working for Dix.

02:12:41.000 --> 02:12:45.000
What are you going to do if you close it?

02:12:45.000 --> 02:12:48.000
I'm a Brigadier, I'm not a Colonel, Brigadier John, rather.

02:12:48.000 --> 02:12:55.000
And I go to Washington and try to explain.

02:12:55.000 --> 02:12:58.000
And back to, we hear what you're saying.

02:12:58.000 --> 02:13:00.000
Now go back and go do your job.

02:13:00.000 --> 02:13:01.000
Yes, sir.

02:13:01.000 --> 02:13:02.000
Go back to Fort Dix.

02:13:02.000 --> 02:13:04.000
I tell my boss, Bert David.

02:13:04.000 --> 02:13:06.000
He tell her, when else that?

02:13:06.000 --> 02:13:07.000
So what do they do?

02:13:07.000 --> 02:13:09.000
They turn the politicians loose.

02:13:09.000 --> 02:13:11.000
And guess what?

02:13:11.000 --> 02:13:13.000
Fort Dix is still open today.

02:13:13.000 --> 02:13:14.000
Is it not?

02:13:14.000 --> 02:13:18.000
When the politicians get involved, sometimes good things happen.

02:13:18.000 --> 02:13:21.000
Train is no longer there, but Fort Dix is still open.

02:13:21.000 --> 02:13:25.000
Anyhow, Fort Dix, I'm Deputy Commander.

02:13:25.000 --> 02:13:32.000
We worked very hard.

02:13:32.000 --> 02:13:49.000
I, boss, Bert David, get transferred to Washington to logistics.

02:13:49.000 --> 02:13:52.000
His replacement comes in.

02:13:52.000 --> 02:13:55.000
He's a guy who got promoted to Brigadier General St.

02:13:55.000 --> 02:13:56.000
I did.

02:13:56.000 --> 02:13:59.000
